The paper proposes nonparametric rank tests based on data compressors, which are commonly used in information theory (cs.IT). The tests are designed to compare joint samples and test for homogeneity and component independence, which are common topics in machine learning and statistics (cs.LG). The use of binary strings and randomization also suggests a connection to data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the validity of the tests against all alternatives, which is a topic in discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the tests could potentially be applied to network analysis and graph algorithms, which fall under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC).
